{"id":"1105.4814","submitter":"Da-Chuang Li","authors":"Da-Chuang Li, Chun-Hua Yuan, Zhuo-Liang Cao, Weiping Zhang","title":"Storage and retrieval of continuous-variable polarization-entangled\n  cluster states in atomic ensembles","comments":"6 pages, 4 figures","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. A 84, 022328 (2011)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevA.84.022328","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We present a proposal for storing and retrieving a continuous-variable\nquadripartite polarization-entangled cluster state, using macroscopic atomic\nensembles in a magnetic field. The Larmor precession of the atomic spins leads\nto a symmetry between the atomic canonical operators. In this scheme, each of\nthe four spatially separated pulses passes twice through the respective\nensemble in order to map the polarization-entangled cluster state onto the\nlong-lived atomic ensembles. The stored state can then be retrieved by another\nfour read-out pulses, each crossing the respective ensemble twice. By\ncalculating the variances, we analyzed the fidelities of the storage and\nretrieval, and our scheme is feasible under realistic experimental conditions.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 24 May 2011 15:59:48 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 25 Aug 2011 04:07:56 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-05-28"}
{"id":"1106.2759","submitter":"Vladimir V. Kornyak","authors":"Vladimir V. Kornyak","title":"Computations in Finite Groups and Quantum Physics","comments":"17 p., to be published in LNCS; v2: changes to match to published\n  paper","journal-ref":"Lect.Notes Comput.Sci.6885:263-279,2011","doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph hep-th math-ph math.MP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Mathematical core of quantum mechanics is the theory of unitary\nrepresentations of symmetries of physical systems. We argue that quantum\nbehavior is a natural result of extraction of \"observable\" information about\nsystems containing \"unobservable\" elements in their descriptions. Since our aim\nis physics where the choice between finite and infinite descriptions can not\nhave any empirical consequences, we consider the problem in the finite\nbackground. Besides, there are many indications from observations - from the\nlepton mixing data, for example - that finite groups underly phenomena in\nparticle physics at the deep level. The \"finite\" approach allows to reduce any\nquantum dynamics to the simple permutation dynamics, and thus to express\nquantum observables in terms of permutation invariants of symmetry groups and\ntheir integer characteristics such as sizes of conjugate classes, sizes of\ngroup orbits, class coefficients, dimensions of representations. Our study has\nbeen accompanied by computations with finite groups, their representations and\ninvariants. We have used both our C implementation of algorithms for working\nwith groups and computer algebra system GAP.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 24 May 2011 14:59:45 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 20 Sep 2011 12:21:47 GMT"}],"update_date":"2011-10-03"}
